\f1\b \cf0 * 
\f0\b0 If you have an 
\f1\b XBox Gamepad
\f0\b0  built by a 
\f1\b 3rd party
\f0\b0 , you can figure out the product id and vendor id from the 
\f3\i USB Prober
\f0\i0  application, then plug those into DWXBoxHIDDriver.kext's property list. (This should be easy for programmer-types to figure out - please don't ask me for help on this.) If you do manage to achieve this, please let me know the product and vendor id so I can add it to a future driver release.\
\
* If you have another device that is 
\f1\b NOT 
\f0\b0 a gamepad, it probably won't work at all. If I get enough donations, I might feel compelled to buy a wheel or write support for other devices. But hey, the source is provided so feel free to go at it if you are so inclined.\
\
- 
\f2\i\b Force feedback is untested and may not work. 
\f0\i0\b0 I haven't taken the time yet to verify if the new force feedback API in Mac OS X 10.2.3+ is able to use the rumblers. It's perfectly possible that they will not work at all without further modifications to the driver internals.\
\
- 
\f2\i\b Earlier Mac OS X versions don't work.
\f0\i0\b0  The driver may work in 10.1.5, but I don't have a machine with 10.1.5 installed, so that capability is disabled.\
\

